<h1>To James Mercer</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon July 19th 1773</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>As I neglected to have the Mortgage which you gave me on the <span class="space" title="space in original source" style="padding-left:2px; padding-right:2px;">[      ]</span> day of March twelvemonths (of Sundry Negroes therein mentioned) Recorded in time by which the efficacy so far as others are concernd is lost to me, I should be obliged to you for renewing of it, or giving me such other security for the Sum then due as shall be adequate to the purpose. The Duty which urges me to make this request will I am perswaded plead my excuse with you for the doing of it, as I have been told that both your Fathers &amp; Brothers Affairs are a good deal Involvd in perplexity and distress towards which I do not want to contribute further than is necessary to my own justification &amp; Security.</p>
<p>As Negros are a very uncertain &amp; precarious Security, and as you seem unwilling to ask any Gentleman to become personally bound, is there any Land unincumberd that you could give a Mortgage on? if there is, I had rather have it, if the Title is clear and indisputable and of sufficient value than Negroes; but am content notwithstanding to have a fresh Mortgage on the same Negroes if they are still living and under no legal disability
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-09-02-pb-0283">[283]</span>
Please to let me hear from you on this Subject by the Post,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0209-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0209-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> and you will very much oblige Dr Sir Yr Most Obedt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0209-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0209-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0209-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>At his death in 1768, John Mercer had paid nothing of the principal and no interest to Martha Parke Custis on the bond for 21,000 that she held from him. As executor of his fathers estate, James Mercer in 1771 gave Miss Custis an additional bond of 1,109.11.6 for unpaid interest on the original loan to his father. At Martha Parke Custiss death, GW took over the two Mercer bonds as part of Mrs. Washingtons share of her daughters estate. See <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ W. W. Abbot et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of George Washington, Colonial Series&lt;/i&gt;. 10 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 198395. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers, Colonial Series</span></span>, 6:261, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 2, 1772-93, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger B</span>, 215. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0229" class="document">James Mercer to GW, 11</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0236" class="document">23 Aug.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0198" class="document">Fielding Lewis to GW, 7 July 1773</a>.</p>

</div>
